<br>
Iommi pulled shadows around himself to stay well hidden--now was not a time he wanted to have to deal with the small halflings. On his way back from Velious, he had heard rumors of grim experiments occuring within Neriak. Supposedly deformed creatures of all kinds had appeared in the Commonlands and the Desert of Ro, terrorizing travellers. He had heard reports of Sand Giants and Griffins, with their skin rotting away and eyes glowing eerily green, holding the usually heavily travelled areas in the grip of terror. Undead, similarly rotting desert scarabs and tarantulas the size of giants were everywhere. He had had to bribe the captain of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Icebreaker</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> with almost every platinum he had to get the gnome to take him to North Ro. Apparently some of the griffins had flown into the Iceclad Ocean, and some of the Giants had crossed over the water to destroy the gnomish outposts.<br>
<br>
All of these monsters had reportedly come down out of Nektulos forest.<br>
<br>
Regardless of where they came from, travel and trade across the Commonlands had come to a standstill. Unlike Innoruuk's minions in the dreaded Kithicor Forest, these undead monstrosities didn't mind the light. They were out and about twenty four hours a day. Save the bravest of travellers (Iommi had encountered only two fellow travellers on his way from the docks in Northern Ro all the way to Nektulos), all land from the southern reaches of the Desert of Ro, all the way up through the Commonlands and Kithicor Forest, had been deserted. Freeport was in danger of overflowing with refugees. Some of the more religious travellers had thought this an omen from an angry Solusek Ro. According to them, the firey god was angered that his temple was so rarely visited these days, and he was exacting his revenge. Iommi, of course, knew better.<br>
<br>
There had also been reports of plague instances in Freeport. Apparently Bertoxxulous knew when to take advantage of a situation.<br>
<br>
Iommi knew this was all related to the experiments he had heard of occuring in Neriak. They were tampering with the world of the dead. It had gone beyond simple Necromancy: they were trying to bridge the two worlds and bring them together. The Queen of the Necromancers had given her life to initiate the massive spell that needed to be performed in order to tear the fabric between the worlds, but without her guidance, the fools were as the blind stumbling around in the dark. Iommi knew of the spell needed to create the bridge. Indeed, he could perform it. He also knew how to counter it, and that was what he had come for.<br>
